	<p>
		We can also imagine breaking each of the chips into wedges and using them for addition and subtraction of
		fractions. And since decimals are just fractions, we can also imagine using them with decimals. Not that we
		would actually do that, but this is is conceptually possible. 
	</p>
	<aside>
		<p>
			Unless the chips were fairly large to begin with, this would be a total mess to track in reality! 
		</p>
	</aside>
	<p>
		We also saw in the last couple worksheets that we can connect these chips to talking about the opposite of
		numbers and solving equations. 
	</p>
	<p>
		This flexibility is one of the marks of a beautiful idea in mathematics. The ability to take one idea and
		connect it to so many other ideas means that we now have an expanded vocabulary with which to talk about our
		mathematical ideas. It also means that when it comes down to solving problems, we have yet another tool in our
		toolbox. And broadening that toolbox is the ultimate goal of college mathematics.
	</p>
